HajabapN HAjb HjAb Hjb Hjbh Hjbp
The head [or crest] of the kip or haunch (S, A) [of a man, (see HaroqafapN,) and] of a horse;
(A;) i. e. each of the HajabataAni, which project above, or beyond, the xaASirataAni [or two flanks]: (S:) or the dual signifies the two edges of the hip or haunch, that project above, or beyond, the xaASirap [or flank]: (K:) or the two bones above the pubes, that project above, or beyond, the soft parts of the belly, on the right and left: (Zj in his “ Khalk el-Insán, “ * and K:) or the heads of the two hipbones or haunch-bones, next the HaroqafataAni [q. v.]; pl. [or rather coll. gen. n.] HajabN↓, and pl. of pauc. HajabaAtN: (TA:) and in a horse, the parts of the two hips, or haunches, that project above, or beyond, the [skin called] SifaAq, of the belly. (K.)

3 HAq~hu HAq HAqh HAqp
, (S, K,) inf. n. HiqaAqN and muHaAq~apN, (TA,) He disputed, litigated, or contended, with him, (S, K,) each of them laying claim to a right, or due: (S, TA:) the verb is mostly used in the third person. (TA.) You say, HaAq~aniY wa lamo yuHaAq~aniY fiyhi A^aHadN [He disputed, &c., with me, and no one had disputed, &c., with me respecting it]. (TA.) [But] you say also, HaAqaqotuhu faHaqaqotuhu↓ I disputed, litigated, or contended, with him for a right, or due, and I overcame him in doing so. (TA.) And A_in~ahu lanaziqu AlHiqaAqi (tropical:) Verily he is one who disputes, or litigates, or contends, respecting small things. (S, K, TA.) And maA lahu fiyhi Haq~N wa laA HiqaAqN, i. e. [He has no right, or due, to exact, in respect of him, or it, nor any cause of] disputing, or litigating, or contending. (S.) And it is said respecting women, (K,) in a trad. of 'Alee, (TA,) A_i*aA balagona naS~a AlHiqaAqi faAlEaSabapu A^awolaY, or AlHaqaAy^iqi: (K:) accord. to some, AlHqAq here means the same as AlmuHaAq~ap: accord. to others, it properly signifies the camels thus called: and so AlHqAy^q;
this [likewise] being a pl. of Hiq~apN↓; or it is pl. of HaqiyqapN↓. (TA. [See art. nS; in which this trad. is more fully, but somewhat differently, cited; and fully explained.]) ＝ -A2- [Also, app., He acted seriously, or in earnest, with him in an affair: see 3 in art. jd: and see also 2 above, last signification.]
